    slug: "shadow-shoot-rules",
    title: "Shadow Shoot Rules",
    loops: ["Internal Training Loop"],
    purpose: "What trainees and new contractors do (and don't do) on their first shoots.",
    ownerRole: "owner",
    whenToUse: "",
    trigger: "progression: Most trainees move through the three modes in 4-6 shoots. Some take 10. Pace is determined by the producer, not the trainee.",
    inputsNeeded: "",
    content: "## The Three Modes\n\n### Shoot 1 — Pure Shadow\n\nWatch only. No touching gear. No talking to talent. Sit by the producer monitor. Take notes. Ask questions *after*, not during.\n\n### Shoot 2 — Assist\n\nCarry gear. Fetch water. Run the slate. Wrap cables. Still no talking to talent unless asked directly.\n\n### Shoot 3 — Owned Task\n\nOne specific job — sound op, second-cam, B-roll lead. Owned end-to-end, with the producer ready to backstop. Debrief immediately after.\n\n## Rules That Apply All Three Shoots\n\n- [ ] Phone in airplane mode for the duration of rolling\n- [ ] No social posting from set — ever — without producer approval\n- [ ] Never speak directly to the talent unless the producer hands off\n- [ ] Never override a senior crew member's call in front of the client\n- [ ] Wear PHP gear or all-black neutrals — no logos from other brands\n- [ ] Eat what crew eats, when crew eats — no separate lunch run\n- [ ] The producer is the only point of escalation\n\n## The Debrief Questions\n\nAfter every shadow shoot, the producer asks the trainee three questions:\n\n1. What's one thing you'd want to do differently if you ran this shoot?\n2. What's one thing you'd steal forever?\n3. What didn't make sense at the time but does now?\n\nLogged in /09_INTERNAL/Onboarding/[Name]/Shoot_Debriefs/.",
